a module-level constant. This is actually worse than using `process.env.CLIENT_U
RL` directly because `registerAs` configs might not be available at module load 
time.\n\nBut wait, in NestJS, `registerAs` returns a function that can be called
. It doesn\'t depend on the ConfigModule being initialized - it just returns the
factory function. The actual values come from `process.env` which is available a
t module load time. So technically `appConfig().clientUrl` works the same as `pr
ocess.env.CLIENT_URL`.\n\nHowever, the more NestJS-idiomatic way would be to inj
ect `ConfigService` and use it in the constructor or method. But the `MatchingGa
