ns` (cache hit path):\n```typescript\navatar_url: p.avatar_url ?? "",\n```\n\nAl
so good.\n\nLet me look at the `matching.service.ts` `queryCandidatesFromDb` SQL
again more carefully.\n\nActually, I notice something. The SQL query calculates 
the Haversine distance THREE times:\n1. Once in the SELECT clause (as `distance`
)\n2. Once in the score calculation (inside `LEAST(...)`)\n3. Once in the WHERE 
clause\n\nThis is inefficient. In MySQL, you can\'t reference an alias in the WH
ERE clause, but you can use HAVING. However, the current implementation works - 
it\'s just slower than necessary. For MVP with a limit of 20, this might be acce
ptable.\n\nWait, looking at the SQL more carefully:\n```sql\nSELECT\n  ...\n  63
71 * ACOS(...) AS distance,\n  ...\n  (\n    (1 - LEAST(6371 * ACOS(...), ?) / ?
) * 0.5\n    + ...\n  ) AS score\nFROM users u\nJOIN user_profiles up ON u.id = 
up.user_id\nWHERE ...\n  AND 6371 * ACOS(...) <= ?\n...\n```\n\nYes, the Haversi
ne formula is computed 3 times per row. This is definitely inefficient. A better
approach would be to use a subquery or HAVING clause. But this might be consider
ed an optimization rather than a bug.\n\nLet me look for any other issues.\n\nAc
tually, let me re-examine the `matching.gateway.ts` issue. The gateway has:\n```
