n the constructor:\n```typescript\nconstructor(private readonly configService: C
onfigService) {}\n```\n\nThe `configService` is injected but never used. The pro
per NestJS way would be:\n```typescript\n@WebSocketGateway({\n  namespace: "matc
hing",\n  cors: {\n    origin: (req, callback) => {\n      // or use configServi
ce in constructor\n    },\n  },\n})\n```\n\nBut actually, in NestJS, you can\'t 
easily use `this` in the decorator options because the decorator is evaluated at
class definition time. One common pattern is to set cors in the `afterInit` or `
handleConnection` method, but for `@WebSocketGateway`, the cors option is passed
to the underlying Socket.io server during initialization.\n\nActually, looking a
t the NestJS WebSocket docs, the `cors` option in `@WebSocketGateway` is passed 
directly to the Socket.io server options. Since it\'s evaluated at module load t
ime, using `appConfig().clientUrl` at module level is one way to do it, but it\'
s fragile.\n\nA better approach would be to not specify `cors` in the decorator 
